  "prompt": "My phone is not running 3G but 2G is working fine. 3G is working fine on another phone on the same sim. What can be the problem with my phone?",
  "response": "Okay, let's troubleshoot why your phone isn't connecting to 3G while 2G works and the SIM card is connecting to 3G on another device. Here's a breakdown of the potential issues, ranging from simple fixes to more complex ones:\n\n**1. Software/Settings Issues:**\n\n*   **Mobile Data Enabled:**  This sounds obvious, but double-check!\n    *   Go to your phone's Settings.\n    *   Look for \"Mobile Network,\" \"Cellular Data,\" or similar.\n    *   Make sure \"Mobile Data\" is toggled ON.\n*   **Preferred Network Type/Network Mode:** This is the most likely culprit. Your phone may be set to prefer 2G or a specific network mode that doesn't include 3G.\n    *   Go to Settings -> Mobile Network -> Network Mode (or Preferred Network Type).  The exact wording varies by phone manufacturer.\n    *   Look for options like:\n        *   \"3G/2G (Auto)\"\n        *   \"4G/3G/2G (Auto)\"\n        *   \"LTE/3G/2G\"\n        *   \"Automatic\"\n    *   Choose an option that includes both 3G and 2G. \"Automatic\" is often the best.\n*   **APN (Access Point Name) Settings:**  APNs are settings that tell your phone how to connect to your mobile carrier's data network.  Incorrect APN settings can prevent 3G from working.\n    *   Go to Settings -> Mobile Network -> Access Point Names (APN).\n    *   Make sure the APN listed is correct for your mobile carrier.  You can find the correct APN settings on your carrier's website or by contacting their support.\n    *   If the APN settings are missing or incorrect, you can usually add a new one manually.\n    *   *Important:*  Be careful when changing APN settings.  Incorrect settings can prevent all data access.  If you're unsure, contact your carrier first.\n*   **Airplane Mode:** Make sure Airplane Mode is off. It disables all wireless connections.\n*   **Software Update:** An outdated operating system can sometimes cause network connectivity problems. Check for and install any available software updates for your phone.\n*   **Phone Restart:** A simple restart can often resolve temporary software glitches. Turn your phone off completely and then back on.\n*   **Factory Reset (Last Resort):** If none of the above works, you can try a factory reset. This will erase all data on your phone, so back up everything important first.  A factory reset can resolve deep-seated software problems.\n\n**2. Hardware Issues:**\n\n*   **3G Antenna Problem:**  Your phone's 3G antenna might be damaged or malfunctioning. This is less common but possible, especially if the phone has been dropped or exposed to water. Unfortunately, diagnosing this definitively often requires professional repair.\n*   **SIM Card Contact Issues:** It's less likely since the SIM works in another phone, but try cleaning the SIM card contacts with a soft, dry cloth.  Sometimes a bit of dust or grime can interfere with the connection.\n\n**3. Carrier/Network Issues (Less Likely, but Possible):**\n\n*   **Network Congestion:** In rare cases, the 3G network in your area might be experiencing congestion. This is usually temporary.\n*   **Carrier-Specific Issue:** Although unlikely since the SIM works in another phone, there might be a problem with your account or with your carrier's network configuration specifically related to your phone model. Contacting your carrier's technical support is the best way to determine this.\n*   **Phone Blacklisting:** Very unlikely unless the phone was obtained improperly, but it's theoretically possible your phone's IMEI has been blacklisted by the carrier.\n\n**Troubleshooting Steps (in order of easiest to most involved):**\n\n1.  **Restart your phone.**\n2.  **Check Mobile Data is turned on.**\n3.  **Check Airplane Mode is off.**\n4.  **Verify the Preferred Network Type is set correctly (3G/2G Auto or similar).**\n5.  **Check APN settings.** Compare them to your carrier's recommended settings.  If they're wrong, correct them.\n6.  **Clean the SIM card contacts.**\n7.  **Check for and install software updates.**\n8.  **Contact your mobile carrier's technical support.** Explain the issue and tell them you've already tried the basic troubleshooting steps.  Ask them to check your account and the network configuration for your phone model.\n9.  **Factory reset (as a last resort, after backing up your data).**\n10. **If none of the above work, it's likely a hardware issue and you should consider professional repair or replacing the phone.**\n\nGood luck! Let me know if you have any other questions.\n",
